<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-inequalities-in-real-life" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Inequalities in Real Life</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.3 Linear Inequalities
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                            <ul>
                              <li>Apply inequalities to real life situations</li>
                              <li>Appreciate the use of inequalities in real life</li>
                            </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on activity -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        <m>15</m> minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To demonstrate how linear inequalities model real-world constraints in business, agriculture, and everyday decision-making.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                    <p>
                        Guide learners to identify constraints in realistic scenarios, translate them into mathematical inequalities, and interpret the solutions in their original context.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </axiom>

    <!-- Add Activity -->

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <term>Work in groups:</term> Form groups of <m>3</m> or <m>4</m> learners.
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Materials needed:</term>
                <ul>
                    <li><p>A notebook and a pen or pencil.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Standard grid graph paper.</p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            
            <p>
                <term>Instructions:</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                In your groups, deliberate on this scenario and complete the following tasks:
            </p>
            <p>
                <em>Generali Youth Group</em> in your local community has received a small seed grant of KSh <m>50,000</m> to start a poultry project. They plan to purchase two types of chicks: Kienyeji (indigenous) and Exotic layers. The Kienyeji chicks cost KSh <m>500</m> each, while the Exotic layers cost KSh <m>800</m> each.
            </p>
            <p>
                Due to the physical limitations of their constructed coop structure, they can house a maximum of <m>40</m> birds in total. Furthermore, to satisfy the community grant requirements, they are obligated to purchase at least <m>10</m> Kienyeji chicks to promote indigenous breeds.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Identify the three distinct real-world limitations or boundaries (constraints) given in this project scenario.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Assign a unique letter variable of your choice to represent the unknown number of Kienyeji chicks, and another letter variable to represent the number of Exotic layers chicks.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Translate each identified limitation into an independent algebraic inequality using your chosen variables.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Graph this system of inequalities on your grid graph paper. Shade the region representing all allowable purchase combinations.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select two points inside your shaded region and two points outside it. Test them against your budget. Can the youth group practically execute a purchase at a coordinate point like <m>(15.5, 12.3)</m>? Explain your reasoning based on realistic parameters.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Represent your combination chart to the class, justifying why mathematical boundaries are vital for community financial planning.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
            <p>
                When interpreting community or business problems, align your algebraic symbols with common operational phrases:
                <ul>
                    <li><p><term>"Maximum of" / "Not exceeding" / "At most":</term> Use the <m>\le</m> symbol.</p></li>
                    <li><p><term>"Minimum of" / "At least" / "Not less than":</term> Use the <m>\ge</m> symbol.</p></li>
                    <li><p><term>"Exceeding" / "More than":</term> Use the <m>\gt</m> symbol.</p></li>
                </ul>
                Remember that real-life items, such as livestock or equipment, cannot exist as negative quantities or fractional values!
            </p>
        </hint>
    </activity>

