    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>
        <p>
            Linear inequalities are powerful mathematical tools that model real-world situations where there are constraints or limitations. Unlike equations that describe exact values, inequalities describe ranges of acceptable solutions.
        </p>
        <p>
            In real-life applications, inequalities help us answer questions like:
            <ul>
                <li><p>What is the maximum or minimum amount we can spend, produce, or use?</p></li>
                <li><p>What combinations of items satisfy all our requirements?</p></li>
                <li><p>What range of values is acceptable or allowable?</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            Common contexts where inequalities appear include:
            <ul>
                <li><p><term>Business and Economics:</term> Production limits, cost constraints, profit requirements, budget allocations.</p></li>
                <li><p><term>Agriculture:</term> Land use, crop yields, fertilizer ratios, water availability.</p></li>
                <li><p><term>Manufacturing:</term> Resource allocation, quality standards, capacity limits.</p></li>
                <li><p><term>Personal Finance:</term> Savings goals, spending limits, loan repayment schedules.</p></li>
                <li><p><term>Health and Nutrition:</term> Caloric intake ranges, nutrient requirements, medication dosages.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            The solution to a real-world inequality problem requires careful interpretation: the mathematical solution must be translated back into practical terms, considering realistic constraints like "you cannot buy a fraction of an item" or "time cannot be negative."
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Ben is a farmer in <em>Wotee</em>, Kenya who has <m>100</m> hectares of land available for planting. He plans to grow maize and beans. Maize requires <m>0.5</m> hectares per ton of production, while beans require <m>1</m> hectare per ton. If the farmer wants to grow at least <m>80</m> tons of crops in total, write and analyze the inequality constraints for this situation.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Define variables:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>m</m> = tons of maize produced
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>b</m> = tons of beans produced
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Identify the constraints:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <em>Land constraint:</em> The total land used cannot exceed <m>100</m> hectares.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>0.5m + 1b \le 100</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <em>Production constraint:</em> The farmer wants at least <m>80</m> tons total.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>m + b \ge 80</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <em>Non-negativity:</em> Cannot produce negative amounts.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>m \ge 0, \quad b \ge 0</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Interpretation: The farmer must find combinations of maize and bean production that satisfy all three constraints. For example, if the farmer produces <m>100</m> tons of maize and <m>0</m> tons of beans: land used = <m>0.5(100) = 50</m> hectares (within limit), and total production = <m>100</m> tons (meets requirement). This is a feasible solution.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <em>Rogaria Manufacturers</em> manufactures phone cases. The production cost is Ksh. <m>500</m> per case, and each case sells for Ksh. <m>1200</m>. The business has a monthly operating budget of Ksh. <m>100,000</m>. How many cases can they produce monthly if they need to make a profit of at least Ksh. <m>50,000</m>?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Define the variable:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>x</m> = number of phone cases produced
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Set up the profit inequality:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Total revenue: <m>1200x</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Total cost: <m>500x</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Profit: <m>1200x - 500x = 700x</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Profit requirement:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>700x \ge 50,000</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Solve for <m>x</m>:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>700x &amp;\ge 50,000</mrow>
                                <mrow>x &amp;\ge \frac{50,000}{700}</mrow>
                                <mrow>x &amp;\ge 71.43</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Check the budget constraint:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            If they produce <m>72</m> cases (rounding up to whole number), the cost is <m>500 \times 72 = 36,000</m> Ksh, which is within the <m>100,000</m> Ksh budget.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Interpretation: The business must produce <em>at least <m>72</m> phone cases</em> monthly to achieve the profit goal of Ksh. <m>50,000</m>, while staying within budget.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <em>Mbale</em> High School needs to distribute <m>200</m> books between its library and classroom collections. The library needs at least <m>80</m> books, and the classrooms need at least <m>100</m> books. Additionally, the library should not have more than <m>130</m> books to avoid overcrowding. Write the inequalities representing these constraints.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Define variables:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>L</m> = number of books for the library
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>C</m> = number of books for classrooms
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Set up the constraint inequalities:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <em>Total books:</em> Books must sum to exactly <m>200</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>L + C = 200</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <em>Library minimum:</em> At least <m>80</m> books for library
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>L \ge 80</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <em>Classroom minimum:</em> At least <m>100</m> books for classrooms
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <![CDATA[<md>
                                <mrow>C \ge 100</mrow>
                            </md>]]>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <em>Library maximum:</em> At most <m>130</m> books for library
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>L \le 130</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the feasible range:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            From <m>L + C = 200</m>, we get <m>C = 200 - L</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Substituting into <m>C \ge 100</m>:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>200 - L &amp;\ge 100</mrow>
                                <mrow>L &amp;\le 100</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Combine all constraints on <m>L</m>:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>80 \le L \le 100</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Interpretation: The library can receive between <m>80</m> and <m>100</m> books (inclusive), with the classrooms receiving the remaining books from the <m>200</m> total. For example:
                            <ul>
                                <li><p>If library gets <m>80</m> books, classrooms get <m>120</m> books.</p></li>
                                <li><p>If library gets <m>100</m> books, classrooms get <m>100</m> books.</p></li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- If STACK questions are included, uncomment this: -->

    <!-- <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/checkpoint.ptx" /> -->

    <!-- Add STACK exercises if made -->

    <!-- Add static exercises -->

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A matatu from <em>Mukuru</em> to town charges Ksh. <m>50</m> for each adult passenger and Ksh. <m>30</m> for each child. The van has a capacity of <m>15</m> passengers. To make the trip profitable, the conductor needs to collect at least Ksh. <m>600</m>. Let <m>a</m> represent the number of adults and <m>c</m> the number of children.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Write the capacity constraint.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Write the revenue constraint.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Are there any other constraints? If so, write them.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Is it possible to transport <m>10</m> adults and <m>5</m> children? Check against all constraints.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    (a) <em>Capacity constraint:</em> The total number of passengers cannot exceed <m>15</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>a + c \le 15</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    (b) <em>Revenue constraint:</em> The total fare must be at least Ksh. <m>600</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>50a + 30c \ge 600</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    (c) <em>Additional constraints:</em> The number of adults and children must be non-negative.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>a \ge 0, \quad c \ge 0</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    (d) Check if <m>a = 10, c = 5</m> satisfies all constraints:
                </p>
                <p>
                    Capacity: <m>10 + 5 = 15 \le 15</m> ✓
                </p>
                <p>
                    Revenue: <m>50(10) + 30(5) = 500 + 150 = 650 \ge 600</m> ✓
                </p>
                <p>
                    Non-negativity: <m>10 \ge 0</m> ✓ and <m>5 \ge 0</m> ✓
                </p>
                <p>
                    <em>Answer:</em> Yes, it is possible to transport <m>10</m> adults and <m>5</m> children.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>Angie</m> a restaurant owner spends Ksh. <m>8,000</m> monthly on rent and utilities. Each meal produced costs Ksh. <m>200</m>, and each meal is sold for Ksh. <m>600</m>. How many meals must the restaurant sell monthly to:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Cover the fixed costs?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Make a profit of at least Ksh. <m>10,000</m>?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                If the restaurant can prepare a maximum of <m>80</m> meals per day and operates <m>25</m> days per month, is the profit target in part (b) achievable?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Let <m>m</m> = number of meals sold monthly.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Revenue: <m>600m</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total cost: <m>8,000 + 200m</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Profit: <m>600m - (8,000 + 200m) = 400m - 8,000</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    (a) Fixed costs (break-even) (profit = 0):
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>400m - 8,000 &amp;= 0</mrow>
                        <mrow>400m &amp;= 8,000</mrow>
                        <mrow>m &amp;= 20</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <em>The restaurant must sell at least <m>20</m> meals monthly to cover fixed costs.</em>
                </p>
                <p>
                    (b) <em>Profit of at least Ksh. <m>10,000</m>:</em>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>400m - 8,000 &amp;\ge 10,000</mrow>
                        <mrow>400m &amp;\ge 18,000</mrow>
                        <mrow>m &amp;\ge 45</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <em>The restaurant must sell at least <m>45</m> meals monthly to achieve this profit.</em>
                </p>
                <p>
                    (c) <em>Feasibility check:</em> Maximum monthly capacity = <m>80 \times 25 = 2,000</m> meals. Since the restaurant can produce <m>2,000</m> meals per month and only needs to sell <m>45</m> meals, the profit target of Ksh. <m>10,000</m> is easily achievable.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    To secure the County Academic Sponsorship program, a Grade <m>11</m> learner must maintain an overall mean grade index score of at least <m>8.0</m> across four main terms.
                </p>
                <p>
                    In the first three terms, the learner achieved mean scores of <m>8.5</m>, <m>7.8</m>, and <m>8.2</m> respectively. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Formulate a compound inequality statement modeling this average target system, letting <m>m</m> represent the required performance index score in the fourth term. Note that the maximum possible index score on the national evaluation rubric is <m>12.0</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Solve your inequality to determine the exact range of scores the learner must attain in the final term to preserve the sponsorship.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The total average is the sum of all four terms divided by <m>4</m>. This average must be at least <m>8.0</m> but cannot mathematically exceed the national ceiling of <m>12.0</m>:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>8.0 \le \frac{8.5 + 7.8 + 8.2 + m}{4} \le 12.0</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                First, simplify the numerator sum: <m>8.5 + 7.8 + 8.2 = 24.5</m>. Substitute this back into the expression:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>8.0 \le \frac{24.5 + m}{4} \le 12.0</mrow>
                                </md>
                                Multiply all parts by 4 to clear the denominator:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>32.0 \le 24.5 + m \le 48.0</mrow>
                                </md>
                                Subtract 24.5 from all sections to isolate the variable <m>m</m>:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>32.0 - 24.5 \le m \le 48.0 - 24.5</mrow>
                                    <mrow>7.5 \le m \le 23.5</mrow>
                                </md>
                                Since the maximum possible score is <m>12.0</m>, the upper ceiling wraps back to the maximum limit. The final practical performance constraint range is:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>7.5 \le m \le 12.0</mrow>
                                </md>
                                The learner must achieve a mean index score between <term>7.5</term> and <term>12.0</term> in the fourth term to maintain the sponsorship.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A group of women farmers in <m>Makueni</m> managing a climate-resilient greenhouse project needs to prepare a liquid organic foliar feed mixture. They combine concentrated neem extract liquid (<m>n</m> liters) with aloe vera solution base (<m>a</m> liters). 
                </p>
                <p>
                    The mixing tank has a maximum storage capacity of <m>50</m> liters. To guarantee effective pest control efficacy, the volume of neem extract liquid must be at least twice the volume of the aloe vera solution base.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Write down the linear inequality that governs the structural storage capacity limit of the mixing tank.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Formulate the mixture proportion inequality expressing the chemical concentration relationship between the two liquids.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                State the basic non-negativity parameters required for this real-world formulation.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                If the farmers mix <m>35</m> liters of neem extract and <m>12</m> liters of aloe vera solution, determine if this mixture configuration satisfies all functional constraints safely.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <em>Tank Capacity Constraint:</em> The sum of both liquids cannot exceed the maximum volumetric size of the container:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>n + a \le 50</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <em>Mixture Proportion Constraint:</em> The volume of neem (<m>n</m>) must be greater than or equal to two times the aloe vera volume (<m>2a</m>):
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>n \ge 2a \quad \text{which rearranges to} \quad n - 2a \ge 0</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <em>Non-Negativity Constraints:</em> Volumetric additions of farm inputs cannot be negative values:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>n \ge 0, \quad a \ge 0</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                We evaluate the proposed mixture coordinates <m>n = 35</m> and <m>a = 12</m>:
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Capacity check: <m>35 + 12 = 47 \le 50</m> (True, the liquid fits within the tank limits)</li>
                                    <li>Proportion check: <m>35 \ge 2(12) \implies 35 \ge 24</m> (True, the concentration is strong enough for pest management)</li>
                                    <li>Non-negativity: <m>35 \ge 0</m> and <m>12 \ge 0</m> (True)</li>
                                </ul>
                                Therefore, this specific mixture combination satisfies all operational constraints perfectly.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A youth group environmental initiative in <m>Kisumu</m> cleans up plastic waste by upcycling discarded plastic bottles into two items: durable shopping bags (<m>b</m>) and plastic fencing poles (<m>p</m>). 
                </p>
                <p>
                    Each shopping bag requires <m>1.5</m> kg of raw shredded plastic waste, and each fencing pole requires <m>4</m> kg of raw shredded plastic waste. The group can collect and process a maximum of <m>60</m> kg of raw plastic waste per week. Additionally, to fulfill a local retail trade order, they must produce at least <m>10</m> shopping bags weekly.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Construct the primary material processing weight constraint inequality.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Formulate the minimum market order requirement inequality.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                If the youth group decides to produce <m>20</m> shopping bags and <m>8</m> fencing poles in a given week, test algebraically whether this output plan violates their raw material collection capacity.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <em>Material Weight Constraint:</em> The total mass of shredded plastic utilized cannot exceed the weekly collected ceiling of <m>60</m> kg:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>1.5b + 4p \le 60</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <em>Market Demand Constraint:</em> Bag output must meet or exceed the contract minimum:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>b \ge 10</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                We test the production values <m>b = 20</m> and <m>p = 8</m>:
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Market check: <m>20 \ge 10</m> (True, the contract demand is met)</li>
                                    <li>Material mass check: <m>1.5(20) + 4(8) = 30 + 32 = 62 \text{ kg}</m></li>
                                </ul>
                                Since <m>62 \text{ kg} \le 60 \text{ kg}</m> is <term>False</term>, this production plan exceeds their weekly raw materials capacity by <m>2</m> kg. The group cannot execute this plan.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A county health facility in <m>Turkana</m> designs a dietary supplement program for expectant mothers using blends of local nutrient-rich grains: finger millet (<m>f</m> grams) and amaranth grain seeds (<m>g</m> grams).
                </p>
                <p>
                    Each gram of finger millet provides <m>3</m> mg of iron, and each gram of amaranth provides <m>5</m> mg of iron. The combined single-serving daily portion weight must not exceed <m>100</m> grams. Furthermore, the combined mixture must deliver a minimum daily therapeutic target of at least <m>360</m> mg of iron.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Write down the weight constraint inequality for the total daily dietary portion.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Formulate the therapeutic nutrient constraint inequality for the required iron delivery.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Find the absolute minimum weight of amaranth grain seeds (<m>g</m>) required if a portion contains zero grams of finger millet.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <em>Daily Portion Weight Constraint:</em> The total physical mass of the food blend is capped at <m>100</m> grams:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>f + g \le 100</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <em>Nutrient Delivery Constraint:</em> The total iron contribution from both components must satisfy the dietary threshold:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>3f + 5g \ge 360</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Setting finger millet mass to zero (<m>f = 0</m>) and evaluating the nutrient delivery inequality:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>3(0) + 5g \ge 360</mrow>
                                    <mrow>5g \ge 360 \implies g \ge 72</mrow>
                                </md>
                                Therefore, if no finger millet is used, the daily serving must contain an absolute minimum of <m>72 grams</m> of amaranth grains to fulfill the safety threshold.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

